% ... (Let's write code here)
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Visualizing Fingerprint Bit Patterns
%[text] ### Let's graph the "checklist shape" visually
%[text] Now let's visually arrange the fingerprints, which have been incorporated into MATLAB as logical arrays (`logical`), as graphs. We will depict the bit patterns (ON/OFF patterns) of three structurally different molecules: ethanol, aspirin, and caffeine, using black and white bars (or dots).
%[text] By performing this visualization, we can intuitively understand the basic principle of cheminformatics: "similar structured molecules tend to have similar positions for ON (1) bits (similar patterns)," while conversely, "completely different structured molecules show drastically different patterns."
%[text] In particular, pay attention to the sparse, scattered `1` bits distributed across all 2048 positions. These represent the "fingerprints" of the molecules that the computer uses to identify and calculate similarity. Now, let's use MATLAB's plotting capabilities to graphically compare the individuality of the three molecules.
mols  = {mol_ethanol, mol_aspirin, mol_caffeine};
names = {"Ethanol", "Aspirin", "Caffeine"};
%[text] 
%[text] \--- Morgan Fingerprint (2048 bits) ---
figure("Name", "Morgan Fingerprint Bit Pattern", "Position", [100 100 900 420]); %[output:398d1b9e]
for i = 1:3 %[output:group:4e023c77]
    fp   = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mols{i});
    bits = emk.fingerprint.toArray(fp);         % logical (1, 2048)
    subplot(3, 1, i); %[output:398d1b9e]
    stem(find(bits), ones(1, sum(bits)), "Marker", "none", "LineWidth", 1);
    xlim([1, 2048]);  ylim([0, 1.5]);
    ylabel(names{i}, "FontSize", 9);
    if i == 1; title("Morgan (ECFP4, 2048 bits)"); end
    if i == 3; xlabel("Bit Index"); end
    set(gca, "YTick", []);
end %[output:group:4e023c77]
%[text] 
%[text] \--- MACCS Keys (167 bits) ---
figure("Name", "MACCS Fingerprint Comparison", "Position", [100 450 700 250]); %[output:1e81dcce]
img_row = zeros(3, 167);   % Preallocate: 3 molecules x 167 MACCS bits
for i = 1:3
    fp    = emk.fingerprint.maccs(mols{i});
    bits  = emk.fingerprint.toArray(fp);        % logical (1, 167)
    img_row(i, :) = double(bits);
end
imagesc(img_row); %[output:1e81dcce]
colormap([1 1 1; 0 0.45 0.74]);   % White = 0, Blue = 1 %[output:1e81dcce]
colorbar("Ticks", [0,1], "TickLabels", {"OFF","ON"}); %[output:1e81dcce]
yticks(1:3);  yticklabels(names); %[output:1e81dcce]
xlabel("MACCS Key Index (1-167)"); %[output:1e81dcce]
title("MACCS Key Fingerprint Comparison"); %[output:1e81dcce]
%[text] ### **Insights on "Molecular Individuality" from the Graph**
%[text] This black and white (blue-white) stripe pattern is the very representation of the molecules as recognized by the computer. Upon careful observation of the figure, several interesting facts can be noted.
%[text] First, the top "Ethanol" has a small molecular size and simple structure, resulting in only 9 blue lines (ON) out of the 167 checklist items. In contrast, the complex structure of "Caffeine" has 46 bits ON, with blue lines densely packed in the lower half of the graph. This visually represents the differences in complexity and size of the molecules.
%[text] Even more interesting is the vertical "overlap of blue lines (commonalities)." For example, if you focus on the right side of the graph (around index 140-160), you can find several places where blue lines align for both Aspirin and Caffeine. This indicates that both share chemically common parts such as "ring structures (benzene rings or heterocycles)" or "specific functional groups."%\[text\] Instead of looking at structural formulas like humans, the computer mathematically calculates "how much the blue lines overlap at the same positions" in this checklist, determining the degree of similarity between molecules in milliseconds. In the next section, **F04 (Comparing molecules by similarity)**, we will learn how to quantify this overlap using a metric called the "Tanimoto coefficient."
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Morgan vs MACCS — Which one should you use?
%[text] Here are some guidelines for choosing between them.
%[text:table]
%[text] |  | Morgan (ECFP4) | MACCS Keys |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | Bit Count | 2048 | 167 |
%[text] | Resolution | High (expanded atomic environment) | Low (defined structure keys) |
%[text] | Interpretability | Low (hash values) | High (human-readable) |
%[text] | Main Use Cases | Virtual screening, ML/QSAR | Pharmacophore comparison, interpretation |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] **Practical Rule**: Use `emk.fingerprint.morgan` for similarity searches and ML, and use `emk.fingerprint.maccs` when you want to interpret which structural features are present.
%%
%[text] ## Section 7: Summary
%[text] 
%[text:table]
%[text] | Function | Purpose |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | `emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol)` | Morgan FP (ECFP4, 2048 bits) |
%[text] | `emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol, Radius=3, NBits=1024)` | Custom parameters |
%[text] | `emk.fingerprint.maccs(mol)` | MACCS Keys (167 bits) |
%[text] | `emk.fingerprint.toArray(fp)` | Python FP → logical(1,N) logical array |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] In the next **F04**, we will learn how to measure how similar two molecules are using the Tanimoto coefficient and the Dice coefficient.
%%
